Why do tech companies feel that having a "trash" folder is good UX? Like I went to go delete photos for english and I just realized all they did was move them to a "trash" folder for 60 days. Thats not the definition of "delete".
If I had sensitive information and I click delete and it gets put in the trash and people see that information I can't say "No you didn't cause I deleted it". Its poor UX imo

In my opinion - This feature was added to save the user from accidentally deleting precious documents. That's why you'll find that not many UI's use the word "Delete" anymore. On macOS ~and iOS~, the system will say "Move to Trash".
